{"/service/ndnp/cohi/batch_cohi_floresta_ver01/data/sn89052197/0051368096A/1920120201/0865.xml":{"full_text":"JULESBURG GRIT-ADVOCATE\nVOLUME XXII\nGEOLOGIST HERE\nMAKING SURVEY\nOF TERRITORY\nJ. W. Smiley, head geologist for the\nMid-Field Oil Co., with headquarters\nat Wray, Colo., where he is actively\nengaged in the oil business at Wray,\nhas been a Julesburg visitor this\nweek. Mr. Smiley has been conduct\ning investigations near Julesburg rela\ntive to ascertaining conditions relat\ning to the possibilities of there be\ning oil in this territory.\nSeveral local men have accompan\njed Mr. Smiley in his investigations.\nIn our interview with Mr. Smiley Wed\nnesday afternoon he said he was not\nprepared to make a definite state\nment, as his investigations here had\nbeen only of a preliminary nature.\nHowever, he did state that he is not\nconnected in any manner with any\ncompany, local or otherwise, that had\nfor its purpose the drilling of oil\nin this locality, and that he wished\nit strictly understood to that effect.\nWhile Mr. Smiley did not divulge.\nto us anything regarding his investi-|\ngations here, we did gain the infor\nmation that he was very favorably\nimpressed with this section as to the\npossibilities of oil. He further stated\nthat in the event that a company was\u2018\norganized at some future date that he\nwould become interested only after it\nwas proven to be a strictly legitimate\norganization, which had for its ob\nject other than just selling stock,\nand creating commissions for under\nwriters and stock salesmen.\nMr. Smiley informs us that he will\nremain here for another day or so\nLOCAL MARKETS ARE\nESSENTIAL FOR PRO\nGRESS OF COMMUNITY\nThe first essential in the develop\nment of any business is the possession\nof a market. The manufacturer must\nhave a market for his products or he\nA&nnot succeed, no matter how valu-|\nalbe those products may be or how\nefficiently his plant may be operated.\nThe wholesale merchant and the re\ntail merchant may have the choicest\nstocks of goods, but they may as well\ngo out of business if they have not al\nmarket where they can dispose of!\ntheir stocks. The farmer may pro-\nduce bumper crops, but they will rot\nupon the ground if he cannot find a\nmarket for them. The wage carner\u2019s\nskill and muscle bring him no rctums!\nunless there is a market for his la-\nbor. I\nThe questions of markets is the big\none in every line of business and ini\nevery con.munity the question is al\nvital on\u00e9. In our community, which\nmust be taken to include not only all\nthe people who live In Julesburg but|\nthe farmers who live in the surround-\ning country as well, there are two\nsides to the market question. The\nbusiness men of Julesburg must have\na market for the things which they\nhave to sell. Otherwise they cannot\ncontinue in business. At the sam\ntime the farmers must have a market'\nfor the things which they raise or they\nmay as well go out of business.\nWhen Either Fails Both Suifer\nThe merchants of Julesburg can\nprovide a market for the products\nof the farmers and the farmers.can\nprovide a market for the goods whica\nthe merchants have to sell. As long\nas each class of citizens provides\nmarket for the other class all is well\nand the goose hangs high, but when\ncither class fails to provide a market\nfor the other the goose is cooked, not\nonly for the class which is deprived of\nthe market but for the other as well.\ne e\nTRANSFERS RE\nCORDED DURING\nTHE PAST WEEK\nF.dith'\nNov. 16\u2014Wesley Jenik _to\nGrimm, lot Bin block 2, 3rd add. fo|\nSedgwick, Colo. Consideration SI.OO\nand other valuable considerations.\nNov. 16\u2014Thomas R. Flora to Min\nnie M. McCart, E% of lot 10-11-12,\nblk. 1, original town of Denver Jet.,\nnow Julesbm\ufb01. Con. $8900.00.\nNov. 18\u2014Harvey and Mayme C.\nFrom to Esther M. ard T. C. Terry,\nlots 1-2-3-4, section 5-10-42. $7,000.\nNov. 19\u2014Esther M. and T. C. Ter\nry to Mayme C. From, lots 3 and Wi\nof 2 im l';YI':I.l 283, Clarkson's Ist. $7,000.\nNov. 23\u2014Gust Papagianonulas to\nSoteros Chris Papagianonulas, lot 13,\nblk. 11 in Original Town of Denver\nJet., now Julesburg. SISOO.\nTHE FIRST NATIONAL BANK, JULESBURG, COLORADO, CAPITAL AND SURPLUS S6O,OOO.OO\u2014\u201cTHE BANK FOR EVERYBODY\u201d\nconducting investigations, before re\nturning to Wray to look after his in\nterests there.\nAnother week has passed and\nMessrs. Nelson and Braddick, the Den\nver men who were here recently to\norganize a local company, have not\nanswered the proposal submitted to\nthem by the committee of local men\n\u2018n-fvrn-} to in the last issue of the\nGrit-Advocate. We are now of the\nopinion that they do not intend to\naccept the proposition, and in that\ni event the local men whom they have\nI'selected to serve as an advisory\nboard, want it strictly understood\nthat they refuse to have anything to\ndo with the proposition, as they do|\nnot wish to go behind a deal that has|\n|'all the earmarks of being simply af\nstock-selling scheme, and nothing\nmore. Let us guard against such pro\n\u2018positinns. which\u201d would be very detri\nmental to the interests of the people|\nof this community.\nSTRONG INSTITUTIONS\nPr\u2014\u2014\u2014\nLast week we published the state\nments of the financial condition of the\nFirst National and Citizens National\nbanks of this city. These statements\nare conclusive evidence that these in\nstitutions are on a giost solid and sub\nstantial basis, and are a credit to this\ncommunity. These establishments\nstand for progress and are always\nready to aid any progressive move\nment which will result in a benefit to\nJulesburg and community.\nThe farmer has a right to expect the\n!town which is his natural trading\npoint to provide a market for his pro\nducts, and the town is not performing\nits proper function as the tradingi\ncenter of its community if it does not|\nsee that such a market is provided.\nThe responsibility of looking after the\nfulfillment of this obligation rests\nlargely upon the merchants. The\nfarmer is a producer and he must dis-\nI'pose of his products before he can\nbecome a consumer. It is, thereforre,\nnot only right but necessary from a\nbusiness standpoint that the mer\nchants should aid the farmer in trun-|\n\u2018!in;.': his products into money. Other-|\nwise the farmer naturally will have no\n}IJIOHL'_\\' to spend in the stores of Lhc|\ntown.\ni Obligation on Farmers\nOn the other hand, the merchants\n|of Julesburg have a right to cxpcc',\u2018\nthe farmers to provide a market for\nthe merchandise which they have to|\nI'sell, and the farmers are not doing\ntheir duty to their community if they\ndo not- provide such a market. In this\ncase, also, it is not only right but it]\nis necessary to the prosperity of the\nfarmers that they should aid the mcr\u2014]\nchants in turning their merchandise\n\u2018into cash. Otherwise it is obvious|\nthat the merchants will have no mon-|\nv with which to buy the products\nof the farmers.\nThis is a double-barreled proposi\ney 2o s v it eyt AR o e i e R N s\n(Continued on last page)\nSMALL GIRL IS\nBURNED TODEATH\nMONDAY EVENING\nMatilda, the one year and nine\nmonths' old girl of Mr. and Mrs. John\nSchmidt died Monday night, Novem\nber 29th, at about eight o\u2019clock at the\nhome of her parents near Ovid, as a\nresult of being burned to.death.\nThe little girl had been playing in\nthe kitchen, and some burning paper\nfrom the stove caught her clothing.\nHer screams attracted other members\niof the family, but before they could\ncome to her rescue, the little one had\n\u2018been severely burned, all of the cloth\ning being burned from her body. Dr.\nG. F. Ewing of Julesburg was sum\nmoned, but medical aid was of no\navail, as the flames has accomplished\nfatal injuries, and the victim died at\nabout eight o'clock, living only three\u2018\nhours after the accident.\n\u201cA little flower to us was given to\nbud on earth and bloom in heaven.\u201d\nFuneral services were held at St.\nAnthony's church in Julesburg Wed\nnesday morning, conducted by Father\nGeisert. Burial was made in the Re\nservation cemetery.\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF THE CITY OF JULESBURG AND OF SEDGWICK COUNTY\nJULESBURG, COLORADO, THURSDAY, DECEMBER 2, 1920\nA Tip\u2014Do Your Shopping Early\nMAKE THIS A \u201cTRADE\nAT-HOME\u201d CHRISTMAS,\nDO SHOPPING EARLY\n\u201cTrade at Home\u201d is the slogan that\nshould be used by the holiday shop\npers in Julesburg and community this\nvear, and if you will but adhere to\nthis policy the citizens here will re\nceive material mutual benefits. The\nmoney used in buying Xmas gifts\nshould be kept right here at home\n\u2018I where it is needed the most, espechl\u2014\nly so during these times when money\nis so \u201ctight.\u201d We hope to see the\npeople of this territory take advam\ntage of the many offerings of Jules\nburg merchants of holiday goods.\nRead the Christmas advertisementa\nwhich offer good suggestions for the\nChristmas gift. We advise you te do\nyour shopp\ufb02\ufb01l early and thus take ad\nvantage of the large assoftments.\nDon\u2019t wait uptil the holiday stocks\nhave been depleted.\nThe Julesburg merchants are en\ntitled to your trade, so don't forget\nthem in making your Xmas purchases.\nBoost the home enterprises and you,\nas a citizen, will be also boosting your\nown interests. Let\u2019s make this a\n\u201cTrade-at-Home\u201d Christmas.\nI Loyalty to home enterprises is one\nthing that it needed for the further\ne B e Rel\nPROSPERITY WILL RE-\nTURN IN GREATER MEAS-\nURE; BE CONSERVATIVE\nB 7\n\nProsperity, we greet you! You are\nnot far away.\nA study of conditions, both general|\nand financial, compels the conclusion\nthat PROSPERITY, sometime absent,\nis on the return trip and near at hand.]\nThis statement is made advisedly, andl\nwith much thoughfulness by the Grit-\nAdvocate editor. This is, howevez\u2018,l\nnot merely our own conclusion. It is|\njsu;;;mrh-d by those who have grown|\ngray in the study of conditions\u2014those\nwho for a long term of years have!\nmade a profession of analyzing de-!\nvelopments and compiling statistics.\nIt is true that you hear much talk\ndepression; that there is nothing\nbut \u201chard times\u201d ahead. It is true\nthat money conditions were never\nmore stringent that at the present\ntime, but it is also true that the ca\nlamity talk that you hear so common\nnowadays is only serving to make con\nditions worse. Let us be more opti\nmistic and view this readjustment per\niod in a broad way. i\nProsperity has traveled in cycles\nboth going and returning, ever since\nthe history of the United States. At\ntimes Prosperity has come, gone and\nreturned within a single year. At\nother times Prosperity has come,\nstayed for a considerable time, gone\naway, and then returned within two|\nyears or more. No law can govern\nthe duration of these cycles of time,\neach and every one of which is obed\nient to whatever peculiar and perti\nnent conditions may obtain within such\nparticular term of months or years.\nThe Grit-Advocate firmly believes\nthat as a great nation we are standing\non the threshold of a new and greater\nprosperity than we have known in\nyears, and sound reasoning bears us\nout. The present depression has last\nlted long enough for various stocks\nto pass into strong hands\u2014an unhil-t\niin;z sign that the powers which hold\nthem will loan money cheap and other-\n\u201cwise make it possible to re-distribute\nthem at higher prices. That\u2019s onel\n!cxplanation. The prices of commod-\nities are growing less and less. A fewi\ndevelopment of this section. The Mail'\nOrder Shark is flooding the mails\nwith their literature with a view of!\nthe big harvest they expect to reap\nfrom you by securing your Christmas\n|trade. The mail order man has ro!\ninterest in you whatsoever, while the\u2018\nlocal merchants are vitally interested\n{in this community\u2019s welfare. Think\nseriously of these mail order shu-|\nbangs before you turn down the 10-|\nlecal m\ufb01x;chant who is your friend lnd}\nn? r.\ne mail order man will not be with!\nyou at the Saint Nick\u2019s festivities and l\ncomtribute to the entertainments in|\nI h you will take part. We, of this\nRjunity, are as one big, family, and\nhave our interests here in common.\nWe should be interested in seeing pro-\ngress, and we should realize this more\nthan ever as the holidays approach.\nBefore you send away for any of your\nXmas gifts, we advise you to visit\nthe local stores and see what you can\nbuy right here at home. We suggest\nthat you cultivate the \u201cTrade-at-\nHome\u201d spirit this year, and in so doing\nyou will be doing your share to build\nup your home town and community.\nmonths ago, various industries wercll\nlaying off part of their employees,\nL| without reducing the wages of the\u2019\nremainder. Today this remainder of\nemployees still at work, are yielding\nto the pressure exerted by those uuti\nof work, to the end that the workors|\n\u2018uccopt a reduction in wages, in order\n'I that room may be made for the unem-\nploved to get back into the harness.|\nIn cther words, that the plants may\nemploy more men without increasing\nthe present total of the pay roll.\n1 It is well for the citizens of Jules.\nburgy and Sedgwick county to treat\nma'\u2018ers in a conservative and broad\nninded manner for their own benefit\n~as well as their neighbors. Let us\nhe conservative and not radical dur-!\nine this readjustment period which is\ng 0 necessary after a great war, and\nwe will be ready to greet the return\nof Prosperity in a firm manner, al\nthough perhaps most of us have been\ncompelled to make sacrifices that\nI.~evmud hard at the time. However,\nwe have the consola\u2018ion of knowing\nI that we are sailing baek to normal\nconditions,\nI P e\nSIXTH GRADE\nPUPLS VISIT\nGRIT-ADVOCATE\nThe pupils of the sixth grade of thei\nJulesburg Y-b\u201cc schools, accompanied\n]by Miss Alice Doner, principal, made\n1a tour of inpection over the Grit-|\nAdvocate plant last Tuesday after-|\n\u2018lnoon. The pupils were shown the big\nlinotype in operation, the big press,\nIfolding machine, job printing equip-|\ny ment, and other mechanical devices\nused in the printing business. They\nseemed quite interested, and the man\n|agement of the Grit-Advocate was\ni glad to have them as visitors. Come\ni again.\nS. C. H. N. DEFEATS\nHOLYOKE IN FAST\nGAME NOV. 25TH\nThe S. C. H. S. foot ball team, ac-!\ncompanied by a large number of root\ners and admirers, journeyed to Hol\nyoke last Thursday where the S. C.\nH. S. warriors clashed with the Hol-\nyoke high school team in the long an\nticipated \u201cTurkey Day\u201d game. The\nfinal score, after 60 minutes of real|\nfoot ball had been played, was 6 to 0\nin favor of S. C. H. S.\nThis game was by far the best game\nplayed this season and S. C. H. S. is\ndeserving of great credit for the vic\ntory obtained from the fast Holyoke\nteam. The game was a spirited one\nfrom start to finish, but the S. C, H.\nS. boys showed more speed than t.heir'\nopponents, this being responsible for\nthe one and only touchdown made in\nthe first half in an end run for forty\nyards by Quarterback Barnes. l\nIn the second half Holyoke started\nto use the forward pass in an effort\nto even up the score. They were luc-'\ncessful twice and made large gainsl\ntoward the goal, making it look as\nthough Holyoke would eventually se-l\ncure a touchdown by this method of\nplay. But a gloom was cast into the\nHolyoke camp when Julesburg\u2019s star\nFullback, \u201cChuck\u201d Kinsman made the\nsensational play of the day by inter\ncepting a forward pass executed by'\nHolyoke near the twenty yard line of\nthe Julesburg goal. Kinsman secured\nthe ball and with lightning speed\nraced down the field, and would have\nundoubtedly have made a touchdnwn[\nhad it not been for interference from\nspectators who had gathered on the\nMRS. MINNIE HAMILTON\nPASSES AWAY AT HOME\nOF SON IN JULESBURG\nThis community was shocked upon\ni learning of the death of one of the\nearly pioneers of Sedgwick county,'\nMrs. Minnie Hamilton, which occur-\n{red at the home of her son, Earl C.|\n'Hamilton in this city, Wednesday af\nternoon, December Ist, at 3:50 o\u2019clock.\nThe deceased was 75 years, 4 months\nand 18 days'old at the time of her\ndeath.\nMinnie Cedora Head was born in the\nI state of Ohio July 13, 1845. She lived\nmost of her younger life near Streat-\nor, Illinois. Her father was a pionecer\nMethodist minister. She was the\nyoungest of ten children.\nIn the year 18656 she was united\nin marriage to William Benton Ham\nilton of Ottawa, 111. To this union\nwere born eight children, five of whom\nlure now living. In 1885 the family\nmoved to Hastings, Nebr., and in the\nyear 1888 moved to Sedgwick county,\nColorado, where they made their home\nion the table land southeast of Jules-\nI burg for seven years.\nMr. Hamilton died of pneumonia\ntwenty-two years ago and since that\ntime the mother has been making her\n'home with her sons. Fourteen years\n~ago the mother and sons settled on a\n\u2018ranch in Sedgwick county, eight miles\nsouth of Sedgwick, where thev resid-)\ned for a number of years.\nThe deceased is survived by five\nchildren: Mrs. Alice E. Thomas, Long\nBeach, Calif.,; Mrs., Mabel E. Ou'u!\nland, Torrance, Calif.; Lieut. Lloyd L.\nHamilton, U. S. A. Tank Corps Ser-\nvice, now located at Camp Meade,\nMaryland; Frank D. Hamilton, S(-VIL:-;\nSHOPLIFTER FAILS\nTO MAKE GOOD\nAT ROZELL STORE\nD g PRI\nSeveral of the Julesburg merchants\nhave been suspicious of shoplifters,\nduring the past week or so, and lastl\u2018\nSaturday afternoon the climax was|\nreached when Dick George, the con-!\ngenial clerk at the Rozells Clothiers!\napprehended a young man who was in\nthe act of getting away with a pair\nof pants, which he had stowed away\nunder a raincoat that he was wearing.\nWhen confronted by Mr. George, whol\nhad been watching him, the said shop\nlifter produced the pants and prompt-\u2019\nly paid for them. The offender|\nbegged for mercy, which he was given\nat that time. The incident happened\nduring the rush hours at the Rozells\n\u201cestablishment, and no doubt the young\n'man thought he could pull off the!\nstunt and get away with it. Per\nhaps next time he will not be let off\nso easy, and it ehould be a lesson to\nhim. i\nNUMBER 8\nfield in front of the runner, making it\nimpossible for him to get by b:g)l\u2018\nbeing caught by a Holyoke player.\nThis was unfortynate for Julesburg,\nl'as the score would have been at least\n12 to 0 had Kinsman been given s\nclear field by spectators.\nKinsman was easily the star of\n\u2018Thursday\u2019s game, he playing a cole\nlege brand of foot ball and was re\nsponsible for breaking up Holyoke\u2019s\nforward pass, which would have prov\nen disastrous but for his sensational\nplaying. As it was Holyoke's only\nchances of winning were sent lkli\ufb02'\nmering. The excellent toe work of\nl Barnes, the S. C. H. 8. quarterback,\nalso took the \u201cpep\u201d out of the Hol\nyoke aggregation, who were so confi\nidont of victory. Homer Lewton, the\ncrack S. C. H. S. guard also is deserv\ning of very favorable mention for his\nexcellent playing\u2014in fact all the mem\nbers of the S. C. H. 8. squad were oa\ntheir toes and playing real classy foot\nball, putting a surprise into the Hol\nyoke camp that the latter could not\novercome,\nSeveral of the Holyoke players suf\nfered injuries and Homer Wilson,\nmember of S. C. H. S. was forced to\n'quit the game the last four minutes\nof play on account of suffering a bad\n|ly sprained ankle. The Holyoke team\nis not entitled to anv alibi for their\ndefeat of last Thursday\u2019s game\u2014they\nwere simply outclassed and defeated\n|by a team that evidenced superior\nplaying at all stages of the game.\nwick, Colo;; Earl C. Hamilton, Jules\nburg, Colo., one sister, Mrs. Orlena\nHamilton, Kansas City, Mo., one brothe\ner, John Head, Clarinda, lowa.\nFuneral services will be held Fri\nday afternoon at two o\u2019clock at the\nMethodist church, conducted by Rev.\nA.J. Waller. Interment will be made\nin Hillside cemetery.\nThe Grit-Advocate joins with the\nmany friends of the bereaved family\n'in extending heartfelt sympathy, in\nthis, their sad hour.\nSTERLING BANK\nCLOSED ITS DOORS\nMONDAY, NOV. 29\nThe Farmers National bank at\nSterling, failed to open its doors fer\nbusiness last Monday. A notice was\nplaced on the doors by Roy E. Smith,\nnational bank examiner, stated that\nthe bank had been closed by order of\nthe president and board of directors\nand that the national bank examiner\nhad taken charge. The closing of the\nbank occasioned little excitement\n\u2019ahnm, Sterling although it was a topie\nof conversatign in various cireles. The\nopinion expressed by persons informed\n|in banking matters was that the in\n!&fifn'imz is only temporarily embar\nrased \u201c\u2019L\u2018l that m\u2018utto:x:s will be adjust-\n(Continued on last page)\nMISSEMMA MILLER\nISMARRIED HERE\nLAST THURSDAY\nA pretty wedding was held at the\nI St. Anthony rectory in this city Thurs\nday morning, November 25th, when\nRobert Hillebrandt of St. Paul, Nebr.,\nand Miss Emma C. Miller, niece of Mr.\nand Mrs. Frank Popelka of this city,\nwere united in marriage by Father H.\nA. Geisert, pastor of St. Anthony\u2019s\nchureh.\nAfter the wedding ceremony a wed\nding dinner was held at the Popelka\n{home. The table was tastily decorat\n|ed with chrysanthemums and carna\ntions, and a sumptuous \u201cfeed\u201d was\nenjoyed.\nThe happy young couple left Friday\nevening for a short honey-moon trip\nbefore going to Bayard, Nebr., where\nMr. Hillebrandt has a position with\nthe Great Western Sugar Co. The\nGrit-Advocate joins with the friends\nof these newly-weds in extending con\ngratulations and best wishes for a\nhappy journey upon the sea of matri\nmony.","height":"20736","width":"14208"}}
